  "answer": "In \"The Ruin,\" an anonymous Old English elegy contemplating the remnants of a Roman city (likely Bath), the speaker refuses to name the place, universalizing its decay as an emblem of *wyrd* (fate). The most charged line opens the poem with stark wonder at inexorable destruction: \"Wondrous is this wall-stone, by Wyrd broken;\"[^1] followed immediately by \"Strongholds shattered, the work of giants crumbles.\"[^2] This anonymity commits the speaker to philosophical detachment: the ruins embody timeless mutability, a *memento mori* for all earthly glory, stripped of parochial history to emphasize inevitable entropy over any specific cultural loss.[^3]\n\nIqbal's \"Saqaliya\" (from *Bang-e-Dara Part 2*) explicitly names Sicily as the \"grave of Hejazi civilization,\" lamenting its fall from Arab-Islamic splendor under Muslim rule.[^4] The most charged line is the direct apostrophe: \"Ah, O Sicily!\"[^5]—a visceral cry that personifies the island, blending eroticized praise (\"You are the honor of the sea\") with grief.[^6] Naming commits Iqbal's speaker to historical specificity and revivalist activism: Sicily evokes a recoverable Muslim golden age (e.g., echoing conquests by \"desert-dwellers\" whose \"thunderous echoes\" recall the *takbir*), urging communal mourning and renewal rather than abstract fatalism.[^7]\n\n[^1]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 [*The Ruin*], [p-d0d2bd](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n\n[^2]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 [*The Ruin*], [p-d0d2bd](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd).\n\n[^3]: *Old English Elegies*, ch. 16 [*The Ruin*], [full passage](/works/unknown-old-english-elegies-d5fe9e/16-wraetlic-is-thes-wealstan-wyrde-yebraecon-burgsted/translation/#p-d0d2bd;p-ba51da;p-dfdbda).\n\n[^4]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 [*Saqaliya*], [p-08760e](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-08760e).\n\n[^5]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 [*Saqaliya*], [p-379aeb](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-379aeb).\n\n[^6]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 [*Saqaliya*], [p-379aeb](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-379aeb).\n\n[^7]: *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, ch. 21 [*Saqaliya*], [p-ac137c](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-ac137c); [p-26728b](/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/21-saqaliya/translation/#p-26728b).",
